,
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="116">Gen: Char: Jaws scythe shaped, pointed, and finely serrated; head oblong, notched behind; eyes very large situated at the anterior extremity of the head; antennae rising between the eyes; abdominal pedicle slightly raised.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="117" pageNumber="116">
I cannot class this remarkable ant as an 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24840" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Odontomachus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Odontomachus Latreille" lsidName-HNS="Odontomachus Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Odontomachus</taxonomicName>
, and have therefore been compelled to institute a new genus for its 
<pageStartToken pageNumber="117">reception</pageStartToken>
; some of the characters given may not be generic, but till other species are discovered it is difficult to say which are, and which are not of generic value.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
